Guide  Loading Data

Node Parsers / Text Splitters

Learn how to use Node Parsers and Text Splitters to extract data from documents.

Node parsers are a simple abstraction that take a list of documents, and chunk them into  Node  objects,
such that each node is a specific chunk of the parent document. When a document is broken into nodes, all
of it's attributes are inherited to the children nodes (i.e.  metadata  , text and metadata templates,
etc.). You can read more about  Node  and  Document  properties here .

<L=8V#7>NodeParser</L> <I=7>
The  NodeParser  in LlamaIndex is responsible for splitting  Document  objects into more manageable
 Node  objects.

By default, we will use  Settings.nodeParser  to split the document into nodes. You can also assign a
custom  NodeParser  to the  Settings  object.

 

```typescript
import { TextFileReader } from '@llamaindex/readers/text'
import { SentenceSplitter } from '@llamaindex/core/node-parser';
import { Settings } from 'llamaindex';
 
const nodeParser = new SentenceSplitter();
Settings.GlobalSettings.nodeParser: NodeParsernodeParser = nodeParser;
 
```

<L=8V#8>TextSplitter</L> <I=8>
The underlying text splitter will split text by sentences. It can also be used as a standalone module for
splitting raw text.

 

```typescript
import { SentenceSplitter } from "@llamaindex/core/node-parser";
 
const splitter = new SentenceSplitter({ chunkSize: 1 });
 
const const texts: stringtexts = splitter.splitText("Hello World");
 
```

<L=8V#9>MarkdownNodeParser</L> <I=9>
The  MarkdownNodeParser  is a more advanced  NodeParser  that can handle markdown documents. It will
split the markdown into nodes and then parse the nodes into a  Document  object.

with reader

with node:fs

 

```typescript
import { MarkdownNodeParser } from "@llamaindex/core/node-parser";
import { MarkdownReader } from '@llamaindex/readers/markdown'
 
const reader = new MarkdownReader();
const markdownNodeParser = new MarkdownNodeParser();
 
const documents = await reader.loadData('path/to/file.md');
const const parsedDocuments: BaseNode<Metadata>parsedDocuments = markdownNodeParser(documents);
 
```

<L=8V#a>CodeSplitter</L> <I=a>
The  CodeSplitter  is a more advanced  NodeParser  that can handle code documents. It will split the code
by AST nodes and then parse the nodes into a  Document  object.

with reader

with node:fs

 

```typescript
import { TextFileReader } from '@llamaindex/readers/text'
import { CodeSplitter } from '@llamaindex/node-parser/code'
import Parser from "tree-sitter";
import TS from "tree-sitter-typescript";
 
const parser = new Parser();
parser.setLanguage(TS.typescript);
const codeSplitter = new CodeSplitter({
 getParser: () => parser,
});
const reader = new TextFileReader();
const documents = await reader.loadData('path/to/file.ts');
 
const const parsedDocuments: BaseNode<Metadata>parsedDocuments = codeSplitter(documents);
 
```

Try it out ⬇️

 Use it in browser

